**You Need More than Just a Great Product**

**Why Great Products Don’t Sell Themselves**

Have you ever stumbled across a really good brand of shoes and wondered why you had never heard about them before? Suddenly, they become your go-to brand and you’re buying them in bulk--they’re that good\!

Or perhaps your friends took you out to a great pizza parlor that, though it had been in town for years, you had never heard of before.

Great brand, great restaurant: Why didn’t you hear of them?

If you’ve ever experienced this, it’s likely one of two reasons:

1. You’re a busy person with more important things to do than notice every shoe brand and pizza parlor.

Or…

2. These companies failed to advertise strategically.

A common myth in the business world says that *if a product is built well enough, it will sell itself.* 

Although this sounds logical, it simply isn’t true. Plenty of high-quality manufacturers, restaurants, artists, and builders have gone out of business not because they provided substandard service, but because they didn’t sell themselves. 

**Nobody knew about them.**

The quality of the product or service you sell is important--you wouldn’t want to sell something worthless\! Delivering well on your sale encourages loyalty and garners the best referrals. Nevertheless, as valuable as this is, it fails to stand as a long-term strategy.

Don’t rely only on your *product* to advertise for you.

Build great products, yes\! Do what you do with excellence\! But then make sure your great products are getting noticed.

Three ways to generate awareness of your business is by…

**1\. Building an Effective Referral System**

This is the most basic form of advertising, but also the cheapest and of the highest-value. Nothing sells a product like having customers give positive referrals to their friends. However, it’s not enough to rely on the quality of your product to motivate people to refer others to you. 

Set up a system that motivates your customers to refer their friends to your business.

**2\. Finding the Best Way to Get in Front of Your Customers**

If you want to sell products, you have to be known by the people needing your product. And if you want to be known by the people needing your product, you have to *make* yourself known *to* them. As you’re probably aware, advertising has majorly changed over the past decade and continues to change year-to-year, sometimes even month-by-month.

These days, social media is where the majority of people are. Apart from the rare exceptions, Facebook and Google are the primary platforms you should be advertising on. The brilliance of Google and Facebook is that they equip you to advertise directly to the people needing your product. 

And even as social media continues to explode, physical snail-mail, live events, and emails continue to be valuable forms of advertising as well.

**3\. Developing a Noticeable Brand**

Make yourself a familiar figure among your customer base by targeting them through various mediums. Interesting social media feeds, helpful blogs, and brand paraphernalia and merchandise are a few great ways to surround your customers with your name and logo.

It’s important to build great products, but unfortunately great products don’t sell themselves. Do more than build a great product: Build a great brand around your great product\!

**Matt’s Original Memo:**

* Refuting this idea that if you build it, they will come. Build a better mousetrap, etc. That building a quality product is all the advertising/marketing you need.
